
[1]reprieve

   REPRIE'VE, v.t. [I know not the origin of this word.]

   1. To respit after sentence of death; to suspend or delay the execution
   of for a time; as, to reprieve a criminal for thirty days.

   He reprieves the sinner from time to time.

   2. To grant a respit to; to relieve for a time for any suffering.

   Company, though it may reprieve a man from his melancholy, yet cannot
   secure a man from his conscience.

                                REPRIE'VE, n.

   1. The temporary suspension of the execution of sentence of death on a
   criminal.

   2. Respit; interval of ease or relief.

   All that I ask is but a short reprieve, till I forgot to love, and
   learn to grieve.
